title: User-submitted feedback for tpm-the-world-of-programming
body:
Clover Ross (clover.ross95@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Server-side frameworks, part II: Python, C#, PHP and Ruby"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/tpm-the-world-of-programming-v1/checkpoint/18

Course code: tpm-the-world-of-programming

Content:


    This is not really an issue so much as it is a criticism, or maybe just my personal opinion. The last question on this quiz asked whether a TPM is expected to memorize information about frameworks. The answer was "no, but you should be curious about the technologies involved." 

Forgive me if this is a radical or immature take, but I completely disagree with this. I wouldn't trust a restaurant manager who was only "curious" about food production. I wouldn't trust a construction manager who was only "curious" about engineering. I think the difficulty involved with simply knowing information about technology is highly overrated - in my opinion, a TPM should have a close familiarity with the technology involved in the development process. I only consider myself a good project manager for video games because I understand the development process from start to finish - and I wouldn't trust anyone to manage a project of mine that didn't have a better understanding of creating a game than myself.

    I don't think this quiz for the assignment is actually a very good practice of emotional intelligence. It might delude students into thinking that this is an accurate way to read emotions on faces... it clearly is not.

Name: "The big picture: project, program, portfolio"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/tpm-project-life-cycle-v1/checkpoint/2

Course code: tpm-project-life-cycle

Content:


    There should be ?s at the end of these bullets:

    Allocating resources - how much time does each individual have to work on your project
    Balancing competing demands - are your team members responsible with juggling other projects and priorities in the organization
    Examining any alternative approaches - what options exist for your team members and your organization to get the work done if whats being asked of them is unrealistic
